#include <iostream>
#include <thread>
#include<mutex>

using namespace std;

int amount = 0;
mutex m;
void addMoney()
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 100000; i++)
    {
        m.lock();
        ++amount;    // Critical Section (Not Thread Safe)
        m.unlock();
    }
}

int main()
{
    thread t1(addMoney);
    thread t2(addMoney);

    t1.join();
    t2.join();

    cout << "Amount = " << amount << endl;
}


=========================================================
std::mutex - Interview Notes
=========================================================

What is a Mutex?
---------------------------------------------------------

Mutex (Mutual Exclusion) is a synchronization primitive used
to protect shared resources from concurrent access.

It ensures that only one thread can execute the critical
section at a time.

=========================================================
Why do we need a Mutex?
=========================================================

When multiple threads access shared data simultaneously,
a race condition can occur, leading to incorrect or
unpredictable results.

A mutex synchronizes access to shared resources and prevents
race conditions.

=========================================================
Race Condition Example (Without Mutex)
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
#include <thread>

using namespace std;

int amount = 0;

void addMoney()
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 100000; i++)
    {
        ++amount;      // Critical Section
    }
}

int main()
{
    thread t1(addMoney);
    thread t2(addMoney);

    t1.join();
    t2.join();

    cout << "Amount = " << amount << endl;
}

Expected Output

Amount = 200000

Possible Output

Amount = 143767
Amount = 187654
Amount = 198521

Reason

++amount is NOT thread-safe.

=========================================================
Using Mutex
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
#include <thread>
#include <mutex>

using namespace std;

mutex m;
int amount = 0;

void addMoney()
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 100000; i++)
    {
        m.lock();

        ++amount;

        m.unlock();
    }
}

int main()
{
    thread t1(addMoney);
    thread t2(addMoney);

    t1.join();
    t2.join();

    cout << "Amount = " << amount << endl;
}

Output

Amount = 200000

=========================================================
Critical Section
=========================================================

A critical section is the part of the code that accesses or
modifies shared data.

Example

m.lock();

++amount;

m.unlock();

Only one thread should execute the critical section at a time.

=========================================================
How Mutex Works
=========================================================

Thread 1
    |
    |---- lock()
    |
Critical Section
    |
    |---- unlock()

                Thread 2 waits

After unlock(), Thread 2 acquires the mutex and enters the
critical section.

=========================================================
How ++amount Works
=========================================================

++amount is NOT an atomic operation.

Internally it performs:

1. Read amount
2. Increment value
3. Write value back

If two threads execute these steps simultaneously,
some updates may be lost.

=========================================================
Syntax
=========================================================

std::mutex m;

m.lock();

// Critical Section

m.unlock();

=========================================================
Important Points
=========================================================

✔ Include <mutex>.
✔ Only one thread can own a mutex at a time.
✔ Other threads block until the mutex is released.
✔ Every lock() must have a matching unlock().
✔ Forgetting unlock() may cause deadlocks.
✔ Prefer std::lock_guard or std::unique_lock instead of
  manual lock()/unlock().

=========================================================
Interview Questions
=========================================================

Q. What is a mutex?

A mutex (Mutual Exclusion) is a synchronization mechanism
that allows only one thread at a time to access shared data,
preventing race conditions.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Why do we need a mutex?

To protect shared resources from concurrent access and ensure
thread-safe execution.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. What is a race condition?

A race condition occurs when multiple threads access and
modify shared data simultaneously without synchronization,
resulting in unpredictable or incorrect results.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. What is a critical section?

A critical section is the portion of code that accesses
shared resources and must be executed by only one thread at
a time.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Why is ++amount not thread-safe?

Because it performs three operations:

1. Read
2. Increment
3. Write

Multiple threads can interleave these operations, causing
lost updates.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. What are the disadvantages of mutex?

• Locking introduces performance overhead.
• Threads may block while waiting.
• Incorrect locking can lead to deadlocks.

=========================================================
Most Asked Interview Question
=========================================================

Q. Why do we use lock_guard instead of calling lock() and
unlock() manually?

Because lock_guard automatically acquires the mutex when
created and releases it when it goes out of scope, preventing
forgotten unlock() calls and making the code exception-safe.

